  "doc_id": "37331",
  "text": "Pregnancy is a hypercoagulable state that increases the risk of stroke [CITATION_1] . Ischemic stroke occurs more frequently than hemorrhagic ones. Most of these strokes occur close to the time of delivery, in the third trimester, and at puerperium [CITATION_2] . Although rare, cerebral venous thrombosis (CVT) has a significant mortality rate of 2%-10% [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Pregnancy increases susceptibility to thrombosis, and this risk can be amplified by thrombophilias. We present a case of a 32-year-old woman who developed CVT a week after delivery.",
